      <hedline>
        <hl1>Genetic Discrimination</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bonnie Lipton letter comments on July 21 article on tough choices facing people who undergo genetic testing in deciding to share results with families; says there is also risk that information can be used to discriminate against them in absence of comprehensive federal legislation</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While people who take genetic tests face tough choices when sharing the results with their families (front page, July 21), there is another serious risk.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While people who take genetic tests face tough choices when sharing the results with their families (front page, July 21), there is another serious risk.</p>
        <p>Without the passage of comprehensive federal legislation, genetic information can be used to discriminate against individuals. The Genetic Nondiscrimination in Health Insurance and Employment Act was introduced into both the House of Representatives and the Senate well over a year ago, but has not moved out of committee. Recent Senate efforts to address genetic discrimination simply do not go far enough.</p>
        <p>Now that the map of the human genome has been outlined, we will be able to identify genetic predisposition to disease with greater efficiency -- making the need to pass federal legislation prohibiting discrimination based on genetic information all the more urgent.</p>
        <p>BONNIE LIPTON  New York, July 21, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is national president of Hadassah, the Women's Zionist Organization of America.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
